Feature: the broker vault is the sole holder of the real credentials the fleet authenticates with

  SB-4 vault-custody arm (PDR-017 §3 SB-4; ADR-028 D2). The positive counterpart to
  scenario 06's negative pin: pulling the host credential mounts does not break BC auth,
  because the real Claude OAuth and GitHub credentials live in the broker vault and the
  broker substitutes them. This pins that the broker vault — not the host filesystem —
  is the custody point, i.e. the host-mounted credential path is no longer the live
  authentication mechanism. Lead-owned integration check against the real broker.

@scenario_hash:9eb97a15c63f81f5 @lead_integration:agent-vault-broker
  Scenario: with the host credential mounts absent, the fleet still authenticates because the broker vault holds the credentials
    Given the agent-vault broker vault holds the real Claude OAuth credential and the real GitHub credential
    And no BC container has any host credential mount
    When a BC performs a brokered Claude request and a brokered GitHub operation
    Then both operations authenticate successfully through the broker
    And the host-mounted credential path was not the authentication mechanism for either operation
